        {
            "id": "2f4c01694e9b45718a2ad",
            "questionText": "A scout team uses a compass that normally aligns with Earth\u2019s magnetic field. However, when a large, magnetized ferromagnetic tool is nearby, the tool produces a local magnetic field that interferes with Earth\u2019s magnetic field and causes the compass needle to deviate by an angle \\(\\theta\\) from magnetic north. Suppose that at the compass location, Earth\u2019s magnetic field has a magnitude of \\(B_e\\) Tesla and the interfering field from the tool has a magnitude of \\(B_i\\) Tesla, where the interfering field is perpendicular to Earth\u2019s field. Calculate the deviation angle \\(\\theta\\) of the compass needle in degrees. (Use \\(\\tan \\theta = \\frac{B_i}{B_e}\\) for the calculation.)",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "c1efc7f5c15e45c396a14",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by recognizing that the compass needle aligns with the net magnetic field which is the vector sum of Earth\u2019s field and the interfering field. Identify the relation that expresses the tangent of the deviation angle \\(\\theta\\) in terms of these fields. Which of the following formulas correctly relates \\(\\tan \\theta\\) to \\(B_i\\) and \\(B_e\\)?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a1359784-abf1-402c-833c-c1c6fc69e3bd"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tan \\theta = \\frac{B_i}{B_e}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tan \\theta = \\frac{B_e}{B_i}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\sin \\theta = \\frac{B_i}{B_e}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "eb09e667488a4cdca2223",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that we have the tangent relation, the next step is to express the deviation angle \\(\\theta\\) in terms of this relation. Which of the following formulas uses the inverse tangent (arctan) to obtain \\(\\theta\\) (in radians) from \\(\\tan \\theta\\)?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a1359784-abf1-402c-833c-c1c6fc69e3bd"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\theta = \\arctan\\left(\\frac{B_i}{B_e}\\right)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\theta = \\arcsin\\left(\\frac{B_i}{B_e}\\right)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\theta = \\arccos\\left(\\frac{B_i}{B_e}\\right)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "55cc3ea405aa4712ad8b9",
                    "stepText": "Now, we need to convert the angle from radians to degrees, because the final answer should be in degrees. Which of the following conversion formulas is correct?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a1359784-abf1-402c-833c-c1c6fc69e3bd"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\theta(^{\\circ}) = \\theta(\\text{rad}) \\times \\frac{180}{\\pi}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\theta(^{\\circ}) = \\theta(\\text{rad}) \\times \\frac{\\pi}{180}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\theta(^{\\circ}) = \\theta(\\text{rad}) \\times \\pi$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "896a983013304d2a8c315",
                    "stepText": "Finally, combine your findings from the previous steps. Write the complete expression that gives the deviation angle \\(\\theta\\) in degrees in terms of \\(B_i\\) and \\(B_e\\). Choose the option that correctly represents this final expression.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
